## 1. PROJECT REQUIREMENTS & ARCHITECTURE DECISION

### What needed to be built
A multi-page internal ops dashboard with these pages:
- Login, Overview, Users, Failures, Submission Log (Trace), Scrubbing, TPS, MIS

### Data Sources
| Database | What it stores | Access type |
|---|---|---|
| Production PostgreSQL | main_account, dlt_header, dlt_template tables | READ-ONLY (no write permission) |
| ClickHouse | Logs, events, TPS data, failures (time-series) | READ via FortiClient VPN |
| Own PostgreSQL (Docker) | dashboard_users, audit_logs — our own tables | READ + WRITE |

### Why 3 databases?
- **Prod Postgres** = company's existing data, we can only read it
- **ClickHouse** = fast analytics DB, already has all ops logs — needs VPN to access
- **Own Postgres** = we needed to store login users somewhere, can't write to prod, so created our own separate DB in Docker

### Architecture (Final)
```
User Browser
    ↓
Next.js App (runs on server with VPN access)
    ├── Auth Check (NextAuth JWT)
    ├── READ → Prod Postgres (main_account, dlt_header, dlt_template)
    ├── READ → ClickHouse via VPN IP:8123
    └── READ+WRITE → Own Postgres Docker (dashboard_users, audit_logs)
```

### Key Design Decisions Made
| Decision | What was chosen | Why |
|---|---|---|
| Framework | Next.js with App Router | Full-stack in one project, built-in API routes |
| Auth | NextAuth with Credentials | No SSO yet; approved email list approach |
| DB for auth | Own Docker Postgres | Prod DB is read-only |
| VPN | Server-side only | Users don't need VPN; only the deployment server does |
| Login method | Email + shared env password | Simple for internal tool, upgrade to bcrypt later |

